# Plan: `SENTRY_CUSTOM_HEADERS` for self-hosted IAP support

**Issue**: https://github.com/getsentry/cli/issues/759

## Summary

Two mechanisms to inject custom HTTP headers into **all** requests to a self-hosted Sentry instance:

1. **`sentry cli defaults headers "X-IAP-Token: abc123"`** — persistent SQLite storage (primary UX)
2. **`SENTRY_CUSTOM_HEADERS` env var** — CI/scripting override (same format, higher priority)

**Self-hosted only.** Ignored with a warning on SaaS (`*.sentry.io`).

---

## Format Specification

Semicolon-separated `Name: Value` pairs. Newlines also accepted as separators.

```bash
# Single header (most common — no separator needed)
SENTRY_CUSTOM_HEADERS="X-IAP-Token: abc123"

# Multiple headers
SENTRY_CUSTOM_HEADERS="X-IAP-Token: abc123; X-Forwarded-For: 10.0.0.1"

# Same via defaults command
sentry cli defaults headers "X-IAP-Token: abc123; X-Forwarded-For: 10.0.0.1"
```

**Parsing rules:**
- Split on `;` and `\n` (supports both inline and multi-line)
- Each segment: split on first `:` → `[name.trim(), value.trim()]`
- Skip empty/whitespace-only segments
- Trim `\r` for Windows line endings
- Forbidden names (case-insensitive): `Authorization`, `Host`, `Content-Type`, `Content-Length`, `User-Agent`, `sentry-trace`, `baggage`
- Throw `ConfigError` on malformed segments or forbidden names

**Resolution priority:** `SENTRY_CUSTOM_HEADERS` env var > `defaults.headers` in SQLite > none

